article.headline: Arkansas 84, Auburn 64
article.story: FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Arkansas was able to pull away from Auburn on Saturday night by doing more of the little things right. The Razorbacks posted an 84-64 victory with consistent second-half scoring that ensured Auburn never got a run going. Arkansas also made 20 of 27 free throws and was 6 of 18 from 3-point range. Ronnie Brewer led the way for the Razorbacks with 19 points, including some athletic shots and passes that kept Arkansas ahead. A Brewer feed to Jonathan Modica just before the break gave the Razorbacks momentum -- and helped the team keep a lead -- heading into the second half. "We need big performances from our combination (Brewer and Modica)," Brewer said. "It's important for us to score because it causes matchup problems. They can't double us both and it opens up the middle. We kept on fighting and opened it up in the second half." Arkansas coach Stan Heath still did not see a complete game from his team, but he praised the second-half effort. "Auburn is a difficult team to play because they have so many different defenses," Heath said. "We wanted to make sure we had a high energy level. I thought we responded pretty well in the second half." Arkansas (16-7, 5-5 Southeastern Conference) was coming off a heartbreaking 78-77 loss to LSU on Wednesday and the Razorbacks had to play hard to pull away from a team that started four freshmen. Ronny LeMelle, a senior, is the lone experienced starter. Auburn (10-11, 2-8) led six times in the first half and it took some effort for the Razorbacks to build a lead that would stick. But Arkansas went into the break leading 36-31 and Auburn would never threaten in the second half. "In the first half, we were too relaxed," Modica said. Modica scored 17 for Arkansas and Charles Thomas contributed 13. For Auburn, Korvotney Barber led the scoring with 14 points, LeMelle scored 13 and Josh Dollard and Rasheem Barrett had 11 each. Arkansas shot 59.9 percent for the game to Auburn's 37.3 percent. But a much smaller Auburn team still pulled down 33 rebounds to 32 for Arkansas. Auburn assistant coach John Cooper, who filled in for an ill head coach Jeff Lebo, said he was pleased with his team's 18 offensive rebounds. "It's harder when you're smaller and they have size, but we still have to come down and play defense," Cooper said. Lebo stayed in the locker room with flu-like symptoms. "I had butterflies, but once the game started, they went away," Cooper said. With 3:57 to play in the first half, Arkansas pushed its lead to 28-23 on two free throws by 7-foot center Stephen Hill. But a moment later Barrett made a 3 for Auburn to trim the deficit to 28-26. With the score 29-28 in favor of Arkansas, LeMelle scored after a pass stolen from Eric Ferguson for a 30-29 Auburn lead with 2:01 to play in the half. That was the Tigers' last lead. Hill tipped in a Sean McCurdy miss, then, on Arkansas' next possession, Brewer passed to Modica who was good on a shot under the hoop and drew a foul. He converted 34-30 with 44.3 to play. Auburn made a free throw, then Ferguson took the inbounds pass and made his fastest moves of the half, running the distance for an underhand layup and the five-point Arkansas lead at the break. Auburn got the first basket of the second half to cut the deficit to three, but Arkansas steadily pulled away. A long 3-pointer by Brewer with 10:10 to play gave Arkansas a 56-44 lead, its first lead of 10 points or more in the game. With 3:03 left in the game, Modica made two free throws for a 75-54 lead. "They made shots and played well against our one-two zone defense," Cooper said. Barber, a 6-7 forward, said it came down to poise and effort. "In the first half, we were working very hard," Barber said. "I was screening a lot and got open shots. As a team, we were moving and screening -- simply being patient. In the second half, we weren't being patient and started turning over the ball."
